{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b1bc983f-c130-4786-9a5d-cecc146e8384","content":"For .NET 10 on Linux 6.8 with root, **`perf`** is the best tool — it captures both managed and native frames. .NET 8+ emits frame pointers by default on Linux, so unwinding works cleanly.\n\n**Steps:**\n\n```bash\n# 1. Ensure the runtime writes a JIT symbol map (may already be on by default in .NET 10)\nexport DOTNET_PerfMapEnabled=1\n\n# 2. Record CPU profile with frame-pointer unwinding (30 s sample)\nperf record -g --call-graph fp -p $(pidof your-service) -- sleep 30\n\n# 3. Resolve symbols and view\nperf script | dotnet-stack symbolicate   # or use speedscope/flamegraph.pl\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n\n| Concern | Recommendation |\n|---------|----------------|\n| Mixed managed+native stacks | `--call-graph fp` (frame pointers, lowest overhead) |\n| Deep/complex native stacks | `--call-graph dwarf` (more robust, higher overhead) |\n| Visualization | Pipe `perf script` → [FlameGraph](https://github.com/brendangregg/FlameGraph) or export to speedscope |\n| Already-running process | Send `SIGUSR2` or use `dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling` (EventPipe; managed-only though) |\n\n**Why not `dotnet-trace`?** It uses EventPipe which resolves managed frames well but **does not capture native call stacks**. Since you suspect native code, `perf` is essential.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cfc5d54b-5427-436b-b50f-c0300f6c5d43","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a rich trace with native call stacks on a .NET 10 service running on Linux with kernel 6.8. This is a performance diagnostics question. Let me provide a concise, practical answer.\n\nFor .NET on Linux with native call stacks, the best approach is using `dotnet-trace` with `perf` or using `perf` directly. Since they have kernel 6.8 and root access, they can use:\n\n1. **`perf`** - the Linux profiler that captures native stacks natively\n2. **`dotnet-trace`** with the `--format speedscope` or converting to perf format\n\n\n3. **EventPipe + perf** combination\n\nFor .NET 10 on Linux specifically, `perf record` with DWARF call stacks is the most reliable option for capturing native frames alongside managed code, though it requires proper symbol resolution for the .NET runtime.\n\nThe key is enabling perf map generation through environment variables so the runtime automatically writes symbol maps to `/tmp/perf-<pid>.map`, which allows `dotnet-symbol` to resolve managed frames after collection. I'm setting up the perf command with DWARF unwinding to capture the full native call stack...\n\nActually, with .NET 8+ on modern kernels, frame pointers are enabled by default, so I can use the simpler frame pointer unwinding instead of DWARF. Let me provide a straightforward, complete solution.","outputTokens":1018,"requestId":"503E:243E33:1BC5B5:229B11:69F54F81"},"id":"26fea81e-9dc2-4ef5-a828-a09aa9a5705d","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:12:54.547Z","parentId":"106d58a1-f84d-45d8-bb6b-df0f18353a63"}
